The clarity and color of packaging materials influences the acceptance of packaged goods by consumers. The tristimulus color coordinates (L*, a*, and b*) of the different biofilms was therefore measured (Table 1
                           ). The films were tested with a white plate behind them, so a high L* value is most likely due to transmission of light waves through the films and reflection from this plate. The relatively high L* value (56.90 ± 0.41) of the SPI-MC biofilms can therefore be attributed to their high transparence, caused by low light scattering and absorption. Adding MJ-CDs decreased the lightness and increased the positive b-value of the films, which can mainly be attributed to selective absorption and scattering of light waves by the carbon dots, which had a yellowish color themselves. Adding both MJ-CDs and MJBs to the SPI-MC biofilms caused a decrease in lightness, and an increase in both a* and b* values, which can again be attributed to light scattering and absorption effects by the additives. Compared to the SPI-MC biofilms, the ΔE values of the SPI-MC/MJ-CDs/MJBs films were substantially greater (p < 0.05), indicating a considerably higher level of pigmentation. The overall color change was primarily attributed to selective absorption of light by the MJ-CDs and MJBs, since the light scattering effects would be relatively small due to the small dimensions of these additives. Fig. 3
                           b shows the UV–vis transmittance spectra for various films. The SPI-MC biofilms exhibited a relatively high light transmittance when exposed to light waves below 400 nm, but the addition of the MJ-CDs resulted in a decrease in the light transmittance of the SPI-MC biofilms, which can mainly be attributed to scattering and absorption of light by the carbon dots. After the incorporation of both MJ-CDs and MJBs, the UV-B transmittance (280–320 nm) of the films was close to zero, which can be attributed to the good UV absorption properties of these two additives [45,46].

The mechanical properties of the different biofilms were characterized by measuring their tensile strength (TS) and elongation at break (EAB) values (Fig. 4

                           a). The tensile strength of the SPI-MC biofilms increased after addition of MJ-CDs, and then increased further after addition of the MJBs. This suggests that both the carbon dots and the betacyanin increased the resistance of the films to stretching, which may have been because they reinforced the crosslinks between the protein and polysaccharide molecules within the films. The elongation at break of the SPI-MC biofilms increased after addition of MJ-CDs, but then decreased slightly after addition of the MJBs. This result suggest that the carbon dots increased the resistance of the films to fracture, whereas the betacyanin slightly decreased it. For the sake of comparison, the physical properties (TS, EAB, WVP, and WCA) of the biofilms fabricated in the current study were compared with those reported for other kinds of films in previous studies (Table 2
                           ). These results show that there are appreciable differences between the properties of the films depending on the materials used to fabricate them.
